<m0>n radio call-ins and at book-store signings, Gloria Vanderbilt's fifth book is drawing a different kind of audience.<ep>
   They're not so much interested in the celebrity Vanderbilt (--) born to a railroad baron, wooed by Frank Sinatra, made wealthier by her designer-jeans line (--) as they are the parent Vanderbilt, who lost a son to suicide.<ep>
   The 71-year-old heiress is connecting to them with an intimacy so disarming that it seems astonishing. When the subject is a son's or daughter's death, ``you're stripped to the bone,'' she says. ``It's complete honesty.''<ep>
   Vanderbilt, who will be at Books & Books in Coral Gables tonight, is the author of two autobiographies and two novels. Her newest book, <m0>A Mother's Story<m0>  (Knopf, $20), is the raw account of the 1988 suicide of her 23-year-old son Carter, who threw himself from the balcony of her 14th-floor New York apartment as she begged him not to.<ep>
   Many of those who have come to see Vanderbilt on her national book tour are people who share her pain. ``The readings are filled with people who have lost children,'' she says.<ep>
   But she offers no tips, no self-help guide, no 12-step program to recovery.<ep>
   All she offers, Vanderbilt says, is her own experience. Her own agony. Her own questioning. Her own survival. Sharing, she says, may be more important than <m2><ql>
